VST: Vistra is growing revenue nearly twice as fast this quarter as last quarter (152 percentage points of acceleration), and the entire power generation industry is starved for supply—with bottleneck pressure at 66 out of 100—which means customers are waiting in line and prices are likely firm. The company is also trading at a 22 P/E versus its industry average of 27, while generating revenue equal to a third of its market value, suggesting the market hasn't yet priced in both the growth acceleration and the structural supply tightness that should sustain pricing power. The biggest risk is that the 99% revenue growth is a one-time pop from commodity prices or contract timing rather than structural demand, and if energy prices normalize or demand softens, that acceleration vanishes and the valuation multiple compresses.

MU: Micron is firing on all cylinders at a moment when chip demand massively outpaces supply—the industry's bottleneck pressure is 68.8 out of 100, meaning customers have orders stacked up waiting for delivery—and Micron's 74.9% revenue growth is actually *accelerating* quarter-over-quarter by 54.3 percentage points, suggesting it's taking share and running flat-out to fill that gap. The stock is trading at a 45 P/E versus its industry's typical 67, and generating a revenue-to-market-cap ratio of 5.3% (cheaper than peers for the sales it produces), which means the market hasn't fully priced in that it's the fastest-growing memory supplier in a supply-constrained market. If Micron keeps executing and sustains high-30s to 40s% growth while the chip shortage persists, the valuation multiple has room to expand toward industry norms, especially since its earnings are compounding fast. The biggest risk is that supply-chain relief happens faster than expected—if new fab capacity comes online globally and the 68.8 bottleneck pressure drops sharply, demand growth will slow and Micron's extraordinary growth rates will normalize downward, crushing the stock's multiple expansion story.
